rseus-paragraph-index=3D"1"><div class=3D"paragraph">Suppose we have three =
integers <strong>A,B</strong> and <strong>C</strong> such that <strong>A-B=
=3DC</strong>.</div></div></div></div><div class=3D"clearfix"><div class=3D=
"perseus-renderer perseus-renderer-responsive"><div class=3D"paragraph" dat=
a-perseus-paragraph-index=3D"0"><div class=3D"paragraph"><strong>Proof that=
 the GCD(A,B) evenly divides C</strong></div></div></div></div><div class=
=3D"clearfix"><div class=3D"perseus-renderer perseus-renderer-responsive"><=
div class=3D"paragraph" data-perseus-paragraph-index=3D"0"><div class=3D"pa=
ragraph">The GCD(A,B), by definition, evenly divides A. As a result, A must=
 be some multiple of GCD(A,B). i.e. X=E2=8B=85GCD(A,B)=3DA where X is some =
integer</div></div></div></div><div class=3D"clearfix"><div class=3D"perseu=
s-renderer perseus-renderer-responsive"><div class=3D"paragraph" data-perse=
us-paragraph-index=3D"0"><div class=3D"paragraph">The GCD(A,B), by definiti=
on, evenly divides B. As a result, &nbsp;B must be some multiple of GCD(A,B=
). i.e. Y=E2=8B=85GCD(A,B)=3DB where Y is some integer</div></div></div></d=
